<li><strong>List size (alone)</strong>. A big list of unengaged subscribers costs money and hurts deliverability.</li>
</ul>
<p>Track <a href="/blog/seo-kpis-guide/">SEO KPIs</a> alongside email metrics for a complete picture of your marketing performance. Email does not operate in isolation. It converts traffic that other channels generate.</p>
<h3>Attribution Models for Email</h3>
<p>Email rarely works alone. A customer might find your site through Google, subscribe via a lead magnet, receive 5 emails, and then purchase after clicking the 6th. Which channel gets the credit?</p>
<div class="table-wrap"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>Attribution Model</th>
<th>How It Works</th>
<th>Best For</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>Last-touch</td>
<td>Credits the last email clicked before purchase</td>
<td>Simple, common default</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>First-touch</td>
<td>Credits the original source (e.g., SEO visit)</td>
<td>Understanding acquisition</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Linear</td>
<td>Splits credit evenly across all touchpoints</td>
<td>Multi-channel businesses</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Time-decay</td>
<td>Gives more credit to recent touchpoints</td>
<td>Long sales cycles (B2B)</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>
<p>Most small businesses should start with last-touch attribution. It is the simplest to implement and the default in most email platforms. Graduate to multi-touch models as your data infrastructure matures.</p>
